xamining the dynamics of Macedonian relations with the Greek city-states, he suggests that the Macedonians, although they gradually incorporated aspects of Greek culture into their own society, maintained a distinct ethnicity as a Balkan people. "Borza has taken the trouble to know Macedonia: the land, its prehistory, its position in the Balkans, and its turbulent modern history. All contribute.to our understanding of the emergence of Macedon. Borza has employed two of the historian's most valuable tools, autopsy and common sense, to produce a well-balanced introduction to the state that altered the course of Greek and Near Eastern history."--Waldemar Heckel, Bryn Mawr Classical Review  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCivilization, Ancient. 0aHistory, Ancient. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh  aAegae.  aAeschines.  aAlexander I.  aArchelaus.  aAxios R.  aBoeotia.  aBrasidas.  aCaranus.  aCassander.  aCersebleptes.  aDiodorus Siculus.  aEpaminondas.  aEumenes of Cardia.  aFlorina.  aGygaea.  aHellenistic period.  aHeracles.  aHesiod.  aIsocrates.  aKotys (Cotys).  aLefkadia.  aMakedones.  aMardonius.  aNaousa.  aOlympia.  aPeloponnesian War.  aPersians.  aSalonica.  aSitalces.  aThemistocles.  aThermaic Gulf.  aThrace.  aVergina.  aVia Egnatia.  aWorld War II.  aXerxes.  aZeus.  agold resources.  ainscriptions.  aminerals and mines.  apainting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691215945zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691215945423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691215945.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archiv